# PriorityPilot — Cursor Rules
# These rules configure Cursor's AI behavior for this project

## Project Identity
This is PriorityPilot, an AI-powered product prioritization agent.
It uses Groq API with the `llama-3.1-8b-instant` model to score and rank product features across 5 dimensions: Strategic Fit, User Impact, Effort, Revenue Leverage, and Time Sensitivity.

## Code Style
- Python 3.10+
- Use type hints on all function signatures
- Keep functions under 40 lines; extract helpers when longer
- All API calls must be wrapped in try/except with graceful error messages
- Never hardcode API keys; always use os.environ.get()
- JSON output must be validated before printing

## Agent Behavior Rules
- The system prompt in priority_pilot.py is the source of truth for scoring logic
- Do NOT change the scoring formula without updating the calculate_performance_score() function
- The baseline comparison must always use a DIFFERENT, simpler system prompt
- Never let the agent output unstructured prose — always enforce JSON

## When editing agent/priority_pilot.py
- Maintain backward compatibility with the CLI --demo flag
- Keep the performance scoring dimensions aligned with the system prompt dimensions
- All new features must include a docstring

## Folder Structure
- agent/         → Core agent logic (priority_pilot.py)
- docs/          → Benchmark results and analysis
- .env.example   → Template for environment variables (never .env)
- .cursorrules   → This file

## Testing Approach
- Use --demo flag to run standard benchmark test
- Always compare PriorityPilot output vs baseline before committing changes
- Performance score must stay above 7500/10000 to be considered production-ready

## Security
- .env is in .gitignore — never commit it
- Use .env.example as the only committed reference to env vars
- Never log full API responses to console in production mode
